+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_018gWSWP8Mty8Ny4qYE1ST7n","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Let me think about the algorithm:\n\n**For `countBeamCells`**: Simulate the beam propagation using BFS/DFS. Each beam has a position (row, col) and direction (down, down-left, down-right). Track all visited cells in a Set. Since beams only go downward (never up), the simulation naturally terminates. Even with splitting, the number of active beams is bounded — but could be 2^50 which is too many to enumerate.\n\n**Key insight for performance**: Instead of tracking individual beams, we can work row by row. At each row, we know which cells have beams and their directions. We can use a map from (col, direction) to a count/presence. For `countBeamCells`, we just need to know which cells are visited (boolean), so we can track unique (col, direction) pairs per row. For `countBeamPaths`, we track how many paths pass through each (col, direction) pair using bigint.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The directions are: down (0), down-left (-1), down-right (+1). A beam at (row, col) with direction `d` moves to (row+1, col+d). If it hits a splitter at the new position, it splits into two beams with directions -1 and +1.\n\nFor `countBeamCells`: We can simulate row by row. At each row, maintain a set of (col, direction) pairs that have beams. A cell is visited if any beam passes through it. Multiple beams at the same cell with different directions are tracked separately for propagation but the cell only counts once for visited.\n\nFor `countBeamPaths`: At each (col, direction) pair, track how many paths are represented as a bigint. When a beam hits a splitter, each path splits into 2. When a beam exits the grid, all its paths are counted as exits.\n\nThis approach is O(rows * cols) in the worst case since at each row, the number of distinct (col, direction) pairs is at most 3 * cols."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence